In .NET MAUI, you use the **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** builder method in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
            }));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters the background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS`** — use preprocessor directives to keep platform code compilable.
- **Android** exposes the full `Activity` lifecycle: `OnCreate`, `OnStart`, `OnResume`, `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- **iOS** exposes `UIApplication` delegate events: `WillEnterForeground`, `DidEnterBackground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- You can chain multiple handlers on the same platform builder.
